# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: dask
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:dask/dask-software] Dask was created by Matthew Rocklin in December 2014 and has over 9.8k stars and 500 contributors on GitHub.
[src:dask/dask-software] Dask is used by retail, financial, governmental organizations, as well as life science and geophysical institutes.
[src:dask/dask-software] Walmart, Wayfair, JDA, GrubHub, General Motors, Nvidia, Harvard Medical School, Capital One and NASA are among the organizations that use Dask.
[src:dask/dask-software] Dask's high-level parallel collections – DataFrames, Bags, and Arrays – operate in parallel on datasets that may not fit into memory.
[src:dask/dask-software] Dask's task scheduler executes task graphs in parallel.
[src:dask/dask-software] This powers the high-level collections as well as custom, user-defined workloads using low-level collections.
[src:dask/dask-software] Under the hood, each of these user interfaces adopts the same parallel computing machinery.
[src:dask/dask-software] Dask's high-level collections are the natural entry point for users who are interested in scaling up their pandas, NumPy or scikit-learn workload.
[src:dask/dask-software] Dask's DataFrame, Array and Dask-ML are alternatives to Pandas DataFrame, Numpy Array and scikit-learn respectively with slight variations to the original interfaces.
[src:dask/dask-software] Dask Array is a high-level collection that parallelizes array-based workloads and maintains the familiar NumPy API, such as slicing, arithmetic, reductions, mathematics, etc., making it easy for Numpy users to scale up array operations.
[src:dask/dask-software] A Dask array comprises many smaller n-dimensional Numpy arrays and uses a blocked algorithm to enable computation on larger-than-memory arrays.
[src:dask/dask-software] During an operation, Dask translates the array operation into a task graph, breaks up large Numpy arrays into multiple smaller chunks, and executes the work on each chunk in parallel.
[src:dask/dask-software] Results from each chunk are combined to produce the final output.
[src:dask/dask-software] Dask DataFrame is a high-level collection that parallelizes DataFrame based workloads.
[src:dask/dask-software] A Dask DataFrame comprises many smaller Pandas DataFrames partitioned along the index.
[src:dask/dask-software] It maintains the familiar Pandas API, making it easy for Pandas users to scale up DataFrame workloads.
[src:dask/dask-software] During a DataFrame operation, Dask creates a task graph and triggers operations on the constituent DataFrames in a manner that reduces memory footprint and increases parallelism through sharing and deleting of intermediate results.
[src:dask/dask-software] Dask Bag is an unordered collection of repeated objects, a hybrid between a set and a list.
[src:dask/dask-software] Dask Bag is used to parallelize computation of semi-structured or unstructured data, such as JSON records, text data, log files or user-defined Python objects using operations such as filter, fold, map and groupby.
[src:dask/dask-software] Dask Bags can be created from an existing Python iterable or can load data directly from text files and binary files in the Avro format.
[src:dask/dask-software] The Dask low-level interface allows for more customization.
[src:dask/dask-software] It is suitable for data that does not fall within the scope of a Dask DataFrame, Bag or Array.
[src:dask/dask-software] Dask delayed is an interface used to parallelize generic Python code that does not fit into high level collections like Dask Array or Dask DataFrame.
[src:dask/dask-software] Python functions decorated with Dask delayed adopt a lazy evaluation strategy by deferring execution and generating a task graph with the function and its arguments.
[src:dask/dask-software] The Python function will only execute when .compute is invoked.
[src:dask/dask-software] Dask delayed can be used as a function dask.delayed or as a decorator @dask.delayed.
[src:dask/dask-software] Dask Futures, an immediate (non-lazy) alternative to Dask delayed, provides a real-time task framework that extends Python's concurrent.futures interface, which provides a high-level interface for asynchronous execution of callables.
[src:dask/dask-software] It is common to combine high and low-level interfaces.
[src:dask/dask-software] For example, users can run Dask array/bag/dataframe to load and pre-process data, then switch to Dask delayed for a custom algorithm that is specific to their domain, then switch back to Dask array/dataframe to clean up and store results.
[src:dask/dask-software] Dask's high and low-level collections create a directed acyclic graph of tasks, which represents the relationship between computation tasks.
[src:dask/dask-software] A node in a task graph represents a Python function that performs a unit of computation and an edge represents the data dependency between the upstream and downstream task.
[src:dask/dask-software] After a task graph is generated, the task scheduler manages the workflow based on the given task graph by assigning tasks to workers in a manner that improves parallelism and respects the data dependencies.
[src:dask/dask-software] Dask provides **two families of schedulers**: single-machine scheduler and distributed scheduler.
[src:dask/dask-software] A single-machine scheduler is the default scheduler which provides basic features on local processes or thread pool and is meant to be used on a single machine.
[src:dask/dask-software] It is simple and cheap to use but does not scale.
[src:dask/dask-software] A threaded scheduler leverages Python's concurrent.futures.ThreadPoolExecuter to execute computations.
[src:dask/dask-software] It has a low memory footprint and does not require any setup.
[src:dask/dask-software] As all the computations occur in the same process, threaded schedulers incur minimal task overhead and no cost from transfer of data between tasks.
[src:dask/dask-software] scheduler leverages Python's concurrent.futures.ProcessPoolExecutor to execute computations.
[src:dask/dask-software] Tasks and its dependencies are transferred from the main process to a local process, executed, and the results are transferred back to the main process.
[src:dask/dask-software] This allows bypassing of issues with Python's Global Interpretable Lock and provides parallelism for computation tasks with primarily Python code.
[src:dask/dask-software] However, transferring data between the main and local processes degrades performance, especially in cases when the size of data transferred is large.
[src:dask/dask-software] A single threaded scheduler executes computation with no parallelism.
[src:dask/dask-software] Dask's distributed scheduler can be set up on a local machine or scale out on a cluster.
[src:dask/dask-software] Dask can work with resource managers, such as Hadoop YARN, Kubernetes, or PBS, Slurm, SGD and LSF for High Performance Computing (HPC) clusters.
[src:dask/dask-software] Dask-ML is compatible with scikit-learn's estimator API of fit, transform and predict and is well integrated with machine learning and deep learning frameworks such XGBoost, LightGBM, PyTorch, Keras, and TensorFlow through scikit-learn compatible wrappers.
[src:dask/dask-software] Selected scikit-learn estimators and utilities can be parallelized through executing jobs across multiple CPU cores using the Joblib library.
[src:dask/dask-software] The number of processes are determined by the n_jobs parameters.
[src:dask/dask-software] By default, the Joblib library uses loky as its multi-processing back-end.
[src:dask/dask-software] Dask offers an alternative Joblib backend which is useful for scaling of Joblib-backed scikit-learn algorithms out to a cluster of machines for compute constrained workloads.
[src:dask/dask-software] For memory constrained workloads, Dask offers alternatives, such as Parallel Meta-estimators for parallelizing and scaling out tasks that are not parallelized within scikit-learn and Incremental Hyperparameter Optimization for scaling hyper-parameter search and parallelized estimators.
[src:dask/dask-software] XGBoost and LightGBM are popular algorithms that are based on Gradient Boosting and both are integrated with Dask for distributed learning.
[src:dask/dask-software] Dask does not power XGBoost or LightGBM, rather it facilitates setting up of the cluster, scheduler, and workers required then hands off the data to the machine learning framework to perform distributed training.
[src:dask/dask-software] Training an XGBoost model with Dask, a Dask cluster is composed of a central scheduler and multiple distributed workers, is accomplished by spinning up an XGBoost scheduler in the same process running the Dask central scheduler and XGBoost worker in the same process running the Dask workers.
[src:dask/dask-software] Dask workers then hand over the Pandas DataFrame to the local XGBoost worker for distributed training.
[src:dask/dask-software] Skorch is a scikit-learn compatible wrapper for PyTorch, which enables Dask-ML to be used together with PyTorch.
[src:dask/dask-software] SciKeras is an scikit-learn compatible wrapper for Keras models which enables Dask-ML to be used with Keras.
[src:dask/dask-software] Dask is used for high resolution, 4-dimensional, cellular imagery by Harvard Medical School, Howard Hughes Medical Institute, Chan Zuckerberg Initiative, and the UC Berkeley Advanced Bioimaging Center.
[src:dask/dask-software] They record the evolution and movements of a 3-dimensional cell over time, in maximum detail.
[src:dask/dask-software] This generates large amounts of data that is difficult to analyze with traditional methods.
[src:dask/dask-software] Dask helps them scale their data analysis workflows with its API that resembles NumPy, Pandas, and scikit-learn code.
[src:dask/dask-software] Dask is also used at the Novartis Institute for Biomedical Research to scale machine learning prototypes.
[src:dask/dask-software] Dask is used in Climate Science, Energy, Hydrology, Meteorology, and Satellite Imaging by companies such as NASA, LANL, PANGEO: Earth Science and the UK Meteorology Office.
[src:dask/dask-software] Oceanographers produce massive simulated datasets of the Earth's oceans and researchers can look at large seismology datasets from sensors around the world, collect a large number of observations from satellites and weather stations, and run big simulations.
[src:dask/dask-software] Dask is integrated into many libraries, such as Pangeo and xarray; time series software like Prophet and tsfresh; ETL/ML software like scikit-learn, RAPIDS, and XGBoost; workflow management tools like Apache Airflow and Prefect.
[src:dask/dask-software] Dask was originally developed at Continuum Analytics, a for-profit Python consulting company that eventually became Anaconda, Inc., the creator of many open-source packages and the Anaconda Python distribution.
[src:dask/dask-software] Dask grew out of the Blaze project, a DARPA funded project to accelerate computation in open source.
[src:dask/dask-software] Blaze was an ambitious project that tried to redefine computation, storage, compression, and data science APIs for Python, led originally by Travis Oliphant and Peter Wang, the co-founders of Anaconda.
[src:dask/dask-software] However, Blaze's approach of being an ecosystem-in-a-package meant that it was harder for new users to easily adopt.
[src:dask/dask-software] Instead of rewriting a software ecosystem, Dask's team intended to augment the existing one with the right component.
[src:dask/dask-software] With this idea in mind, on December 21, 2014 Matthew Rocklin created Dask.
[src:dask/dask-software] The purpose of Dask was originally to parallelize NumPy so that it could use one full workstation computer, which was common in finance shops at the time.
[src:dask/dask-software] The first projects to really adopt Dask were Xarray(commonly used in geo sciences) and Scikit-Image (commonly used in image processing).
[src:dask/dask-software] Dask was integrated into Xarray within a few months of being created.
[src:dask/dask-software] It provided Dask with its first user community, which remains to this day.
[src:dask/dask-software] Understanding that there is demand for a lightweight parallelism solution for Pandas DataFrames and machine learning tools, such as scikit-learn, Dask quickly evolved to support other projects as well.
[src:dask/dask-software] Since 2018, other teams and institutions in academia, tech companies, and large corporations such as NASA, UK Met Office, Blue Yonder and Nvidia, became interested in Dask and began integrating it into their systems.
[src:dask/dask-software] Dask received support from a diverse set of sources: the US Government (DARPA grant), the Gordon and Betty Moore Foundation, Anaconda, NSF, NASA (US research grants with collaborations like Pangeo) and Nvidia.
[src:dask/dask-software] In 2020, Matthew Rocklin founded Coiled Computing, Inc. to provide further support for Dask development and enable companies to deploy Dask clusters in the cloud.
[src:dask/dask-software] In May 2021, the company raised $21 million in series A funding led by Bessemer Venture Partners.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] In mathematics, particularly graph theory, and computer science, a **directed acyclic graph** (**DAG**) is a directed graph with no directed cycles.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] That is, it consists of vertices and edges (also called *arcs*), with each edge directed from one vertex to another, such that following those directions will never form a closed loop.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] A directed graph is a DAG if and only if it can be topologically ordered, by arranging the vertices as a linear ordering that is consistent with all edge directions.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] DAGs have numerous scientific and computational applications, ranging from biology (evolution, family trees, epidemiology) to information science (citation networks) to computation (scheduling).
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] Directed acyclic graphs are also called **acyclic directed graphs** or **acyclic digraphs**.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] A graph is formed by vertices and by edges connecting pairs of vertices, where the vertices can be any kind of object that is connected in pairs by edges.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] In the case of a directed graph, each edge has an orientation, from one vertex to another vertex.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] A walk in a directed graph is a (finite or infinite) sequence $(v_{1},v_{2},\dotsc )$ of vertices such that each consecutive pair $(v_{i},v_{i+1})$ is connected by a directed edge.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] A path is a walk where all vertices are distinct.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] A cycle is a walk $(v_{1},v_{2},\dotsc ,v_{n})$ where the only repeated vertex is $v_{n}=v_{1}$ , meaning the last vertex equals the first vertex.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] A directed acyclic graph is a directed graph that has no cycles.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] The reachability relation of a DAG can be formalized as a partial order ≤ on the vertices of the DAG.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] In this partial order, two vertices u and v are ordered as *u* ≤ *v* exactly when there exists a directed path from u to v in the DAG; that is, when u can reach v (or v is reachable from u).
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] However, different DAGs may give rise to the same reachability relation and the same partial order.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] For example, a DAG with two edges *u* → *v* and *v* → *w* has the same reachability relation as the DAG with three edges *u* → *v*, *v* → *w*, and *u* → *w*.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] Both of these DAGs produce the same partial order, in which the vertices are ordered as *u* ≤ *v* ≤ *w*.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] The transitive closure of a DAG is the graph with the most edges that has the same reachability relation as the DAG.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] It has an edge *u* → *v* for every pair of vertices (u, v) in the reachability relation ≤ of the DAG, and may therefore be thought of as a direct translation of the reachability relation ≤ into graph-theoretic terms.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] In this way, every finite partially ordered set can be represented as a DAG.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] The transitive reduction of a DAG is the graph with the fewest edges that has the same reachability relation as the DAG.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] It has an edge *u* → *v* for every pair of vertices (u, v) in the covering relation of the reachability relation ≤ of the DAG.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] It is a subgraph of the DAG, formed by discarding the edges *u* → *v* for which the DAG also contains a longer directed path from u to v.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] Like the transitive closure, the transitive reduction is uniquely defined for DAGs.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] In contrast, for a directed graph that is not acyclic, there can be more than one minimal subgraph with the same reachability relation.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] Transitive reductions are useful in visualizing the partial orders they represent, because they have fewer edges than other graphs representing the same orders and therefore lead to simpler graph drawings.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] A Hasse diagram of a partial order is a drawing of the transitive reduction in which the orientation of every edge is shown by placing the starting vertex of the edge in a lower position than its ending vertex.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] goes from earlier in the ordering (upper left) to later in the ordering (lower right).
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] A directed graph is acyclic if and only if it has a topological ordering.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] A topological ordering of a directed graph is an ordering of its vertices into a sequence, such that for every edge the start vertex of the edge occurs earlier in the sequence than the ending vertex of the edge.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] A graph that has a topological ordering cannot have any cycles, because the edge into the earliest vertex of a cycle would have to be oriented the wrong way.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] Therefore, every graph with a topological ordering is acyclic.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] Conversely, every directed acyclic graph has at least one topological ordering.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] The existence of a topological ordering can therefore be used as an equivalent definition of a directed acyclic graphs: they are exactly the graphs that have topological orderings.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] In general, this ordering is not unique; a DAG has a unique topological ordering if and only if it has a directed path containing all the vertices, in which case the ordering is the same as the order in which the vertices appear in the path.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] The family of topological orderings of a DAG is the same as the family of linear extensions of the reachability relation for the DAG, so any two graphs representing the same partial order have the same set of topological orders.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] The graph enumeration problem of counting directed acyclic graphs was studied by Robinson (1973).
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] (2004) proved, that the same numbers count the (0,1) matrices for which all eigenvalues are positive real numbers.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] The proof is bijective: a matrix A is an adjacency matrix of a DAG if and only if *A* + *I* is a (0,1) matrix with all eigenvalues positive, where I denotes the identity matrix.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] Because a DAG cannot have self-loops, its adjacency matrix must have a zero diagonal, so adding I preserves the property that all matrix coefficients are 0 or 1.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] A *multitree* (also called a *strongly unambiguous graph* or a *mangrove*) is a DAG in which there is at most one directed path between any two vertices.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] Equivalently, it is a DAG in which the subgraph reachable from any vertex induces an undirected tree.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] A *polytree* (also called a *directed tree*) is a multitree formed by orienting the edges of an undirected tree.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] An *arborescence* is a polytree formed by orienting the edges of an undirected tree away from a particular vertex, called the *root* of the arborescence.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] Topological sorting is the algorithmic problem of finding a topological ordering of a given DAG.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] Kahn's algorithm for topological sorting builds the vertex ordering directly.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] It maintains a list of vertices that have no incoming edges from other vertices that have not already been included in the partially constructed topological ordering; initially this list consists of the vertices with no incoming edges at all.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] Then, it repeatedly adds one vertex from this list to the end of the partially constructed topological ordering, and checks whether its neighbors should be added to the list.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] The algorithm terminates when all vertices have been processed in this way.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] Alternatively, a topological ordering may be constructed by reversing a postorder numbering of a depth-first search graph traversal.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] Any undirected graph may be made into a DAG by choosing a total order for its vertices and directing every edge from the earlier endpoint in the order to the later endpoint.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] The resulting orientation of the edges is called an acyclic orientation.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] Different total orders may lead to the same acyclic orientation, so an n-vertex graph can have fewer than *n*! acyclic orientations.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] The number of acyclic orientations is equal to |*χ*(−1)|, where χ is the chromatic polynomial of the given graph.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] Any directed graph may be made into a DAG by removing a feedback vertex set or a feedback arc set, a set of vertices or edges (respectively) that touches all cycles.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] However, the smallest such set is NP-hard to find.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] An arbitrary directed graph may also be transformed into a DAG, called its condensation, by contracting each of its strongly connected components into a single supervertex.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] When the graph is already acyclic, its smallest feedback vertex sets and feedback arc sets are empty, and its condensation is the graph itself.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] The transitive closure of a given DAG, with n vertices and m edges, may be constructed in time *O*(*mn*) by using either breadth-first search or depth-first search to test reachability from each vertex.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] Alternatively, it can be solved in time *O*(*n**ω*) where *ω* < 2.373 is the exponent for matrix multiplication algorithms; this is a theoretical improvement over the *O*(*mn*) bound for dense graphs.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] In all of these transitive closure algorithms, it is possible to distinguish pairs of vertices that are reachable by at least one path of length two or more from pairs that can only be connected by a length-one path.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] The transitive reduction consists of the edges that form length-one paths that are the only paths connecting their endpoints.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] Therefore, the transitive reduction can be constructed in the same asymptotic time bounds as the transitive closure.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] The closure problem takes as input a vertex-weighted directed acyclic graph and seeks the minimum (or maximum) weight of a closure – a set of vertices *C*, such that no edges leave *C*.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] The problem may be formulated for directed graphs without the assumption of acyclicity, but with no greater generality, because in this case it is equivalent to the same problem on the condensation of the graph.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] It may be solved in polynomial time using a reduction to the maximum flow problem.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] Some algorithms become simpler when used on DAGs instead of general graphs, based on the principle of topological ordering.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] For example, it is possible to find shortest paths and longest paths from a given starting vertex in DAGs in linear time by processing the vertices in a topological order, and calculating the path length for each vertex to be the minimum or maximum length obtained via any of its incoming edges.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] In contrast, for arbitrary graphs the shortest path may require slower algorithms such as Dijkstra's algorithm or the Bellman–Ford algorithm, and longest paths in arbitrary graphs are NP-hard to find.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] Directed acyclic graph representations of partial orderings have many applications in scheduling for systems of tasks with ordering constraints.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] An important class of problems of this type concern collections of objects that need to be updated, such as the cells of a spreadsheet after one of the cells has been changed, or the object files of a piece of computer software after its source code has been changed.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] In this context, a dependency graph is a graph that has a vertex for each object to be updated, and an edge connecting two objects whenever one of them needs to be updated earlier than the other.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] A cycle in this graph is called a circular dependency, and is generally not allowed, because there would be no way to consistently schedule the tasks involved in the cycle.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] Dependency graphs without circular dependencies form DAGs.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] For instance, when one cell of a spreadsheet changes, it is necessary to recalculate the values of other cells that depend directly or indirectly on the changed cell.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] For this problem, the tasks to be scheduled are the recalculations of the values of individual cells of the spreadsheet.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] Dependencies arise when an expression in one cell uses a value from another cell.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] In such a case, the value that is used must be recalculated earlier than the expression that uses it.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] Topologically ordering the dependency graph, and using this topological order to schedule the cell updates, allows the whole spreadsheet to be updated with only a single evaluation per cell.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] Similar problems of task ordering arise in makefiles for program compilation and instruction scheduling for low-level computer program optimization.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] A somewhat different DAG-based formulation of scheduling constraints is used by the program evaluation and review technique (PERT), a method for management of large human projects that was one of the first applications of DAGs.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] In this method, the vertices of a DAG represent milestones of a project rather than specific tasks to be performed.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] Instead, a task or activity is represented by an edge of a DAG, connecting two milestones that mark the beginning and completion of the task.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] Each such edge is labeled with an estimate for the amount of time that it will take a team of workers to perform the task.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] The longest path in this DAG represents the critical path of the project, the one that controls the total time for the project.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] Individual milestones can be scheduled according to the lengths of the longest paths ending at their vertices.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] A directed acyclic graph may be used to represent a network of processing elements.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] In this representation, data enters a processing element through its incoming edges and leaves the element through its outgoing edges.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] For instance, in electronic circuit design, static combinational logic blocks can be represented as an acyclic system of logic gates that computes a function of an input, where the input and output of the function are represented as individual bits.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] In general, the output of these blocks cannot be used as the input unless it is captured by a register or state element which maintains its acyclic properties.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] Electronic circuit schematics either on paper or in a database are a form of directed acyclic graphs using instances or components to form a directed reference to a lower level component.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] Electronic circuits themselves are not necessarily acyclic or directed.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] Dataflow programming languages describe systems of operations on data streams, and the connections between the outputs of some operations and the inputs of others.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] These languages can be convenient for describing repetitive data processing tasks, in which the same acyclically-connected collection of operations is applied to many data items.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] They can be executed as a parallel algorithm in which each operation is performed by a parallel process as soon as another set of inputs becomes available to it.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] In compilers, straight line code (that is, sequences of statements without loops or conditional branches) may be represented by a DAG describing the inputs and outputs of each of the arithmetic operations performed within the code.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] This representation allows the compiler to perform common subexpression elimination efficiently.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] At a higher level of code organization, the acyclic dependencies principle states that the dependencies between modules or components of a large software system should form a directed acyclic graph.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] Feedforward neural networks are another example.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] Graphs in which vertices represent events occurring at a definite time, and where the edges always point from an earlier time vertex to a later time vertex, are necessarily directed and acyclic.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] The lack of a cycle follows because the time associated with a vertex always increases as you follow any directed path in the graph, so you can never return to a vertex on a path.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] This reflects our natural intuition that causality means events can only affect the future, they never affect the past, and thus we have no causal loops.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] An example of this type of directed acyclic graph are those encountered in the causal set approach to quantum gravity though in this case the graphs considered are transitively complete.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] In the version history example below, each version of the software is associated with a unique time, typically the time the version was saved, committed or released.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] In the citation graph examples below, the documents are published at one time and can only refer to older documents.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] Sometimes events are not associated with a specific physical time.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] Provided that pairs of events have a purely causal relationship, that is edges represent causal relations between the events, we will have a directed acyclic graph.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] For instance, a Bayesian network represents a system of probabilistic events as vertices in a directed acyclic graph, in which the likelihood of an event may be calculated from the likelihoods of its predecessors in the DAG.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] In this context, the moral graph of a DAG is the undirected graph created by adding an (undirected) edge between all parents of the same vertex (sometimes called *marrying*), and then replacing all directed edges by undirected edges.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] Another type of graph with a similar causal structure is an influence diagram, the vertices of which represent either decisions to be made or unknown information, and the edges of which represent causal influences from one vertex to another.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] In epidemiology, for instance, these diagrams are often used to estimate the expected value of different choices for intervention.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] That is in any application represented by a directed acyclic graph there is a causal structure, either an explicit order or time in the example or an order which can be derived from graph structure.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] This follows because all directed acyclic graphs have a topological ordering, i.e. there is at least one way to put the vertices in an order such that all edges point in the same direction along that order.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] Family trees may be seen as directed acyclic graphs, with a vertex for each family member and an edge for each parent-child relationship.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] Despite the name, these graphs are not necessarily trees because of the possibility of marriages between relatives (so a child has a common ancestor on both the mother's and father's side) causing pedigree collapse.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] The graphs of matrilineal descent (mother-daughter relationships) and patrilineal descent (father-son relationships) are trees within this graph.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] Because no one can become their own ancestor, family trees are acyclic.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] The version history of a distributed revision control system, such as Git, generally has the structure of a directed acyclic graph, in which there is a vertex for each revision and an edge connecting pairs of revisions that were directly derived from each other.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] These are not trees in general due to merges.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] In many randomized algorithms in computational geometry, the algorithm maintains a *history DAG* representing the version history of a geometric structure over the course of a sequence of changes to the structure.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] For instance in a randomized incremental algorithm for Delaunay triangulation, the triangulation changes by replacing one triangle by three smaller triangles when each point is added, and by "flip" operations that replace pairs of triangles by a different pair of triangles.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] The history DAG for this algorithm has a vertex for each triangle constructed as part of the algorithm, and edges from each triangle to the two or three other triangles that replace it.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] This structure allows point location queries to be answered efficiently: to find the location of a query point q in the Delaunay triangulation, follow a path in the history DAG, at each step moving to the replacement triangle that contains q.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] The final triangle reached in this path must be the Delaunay triangle that contains q.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] In a citation graph the vertices are documents with a single publication date.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] The edges represent the citations from the bibliography of one document to other necessarily earlier documents.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] The classic example comes from the citations between academic papers as pointed out in the 1965 article "Networks of Scientific Papers" by Derek J. de Solla Price who went on to produce the first model of a citation network, the Price model.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] In this case the citation count of a paper is just the in-degree of the corresponding vertex of the citation network.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] This is an important measure in citation analysis.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] Court judgements provide another example as judges support their conclusions in one case by recalling other earlier decisions made in previous cases.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] A final example is provided by patents which must refer to earlier prior art, earlier patents which are relevant to the current patent claim.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] By taking the special properties of directed acyclic graphs into account, one can analyse citation networks with techniques not available when analysing the general graphs considered in many studies using network analysis.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] For instance transitive reduction gives new insights into the citation distributions found in different applications highlighting clear differences in the mechanisms creating citations networks in different contexts.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] Another technique is main path analysis, which traces the citation links and suggests the most significant citation chains in a given citation graph.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] The Price model is too simple to be a realistic model of a citation network but it is simple enough to allow for analytic solutions for some of its properties.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] Many of these can be found by using results derived from the undirected version of the Price model, the Barabási–Albert model.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] However, since Price's model gives a directed acyclic graph, it is a useful model when looking for analytic calculations of properties unique to directed acyclic graphs.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] For instance, the length of the longest path, from the n-th node added to the network to the first node in the network, scales as $\ln(n)$ .
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] Directed acyclic graphs may also be used as a compact representation of a collection of sequences.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] In this type of application, one finds a DAG in which the paths form the given sequences.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] When many of the sequences share the same subsequences, these shared subsequences can be represented by a shared part of the DAG, allowing the representation to use less space than it would take to list out all of the sequences separately.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] For example, the directed acyclic word graph is a data structure in computer science formed by a directed acyclic graph with a single source and with edges labeled by letters or symbols; the paths from the source to the sinks in this graph represent a set of strings, such as English words.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] Any set of sequences can be represented as paths in a tree, by forming a tree vertex for every prefix of a sequence and making the parent of one of these vertices represent the sequence with one fewer element; the tree formed in this way for a set of strings is called a trie.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] Similarly, a binary search tree can be viewed as a rooted DAG where paths represent sorted orderings of keys, though it lacks the path-merging compression found in more complex DAGs.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] A directed acyclic word graph saves space over a trie by allowing paths to diverge and rejoin, so that a set of words with the same possible suffixes can be represented by a single tree vertex.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] The same idea of using a DAG to represent a family of paths occurs in the binary decision diagram, a DAG-based data structure for representing binary functions.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] In a binary decision diagram, each non-sink vertex is labeled by the name of a binary variable, and each sink and each edge is labeled by a 0 or 1.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] The function value for any truth assignment to the variables is the value at the sink found by following a path, starting from the single source vertex, that at each non-sink vertex follows the outgoing edge labeled with the value of that vertex's variable.
[src:dask/directed-acyclic-graph] Just as directed acyclic word graphs can be viewed as a compressed form of tries, binary decision diagrams can be viewed as compressed forms of decision trees that save space by allowing paths to rejoin when they agree on the results of all remaining decisions.
[src:dask/distributed-computing] The components of a distributed system communicate and coordinate their actions by passing messages to one another in order to achieve a common goal.
[src:dask/distributed-computing] Three challenges of distributed systems are: maintaining concurrency of components, overcoming the lack of a global clock, and managing the independent failure of components.
[src:dask/distributed-computing] When a component of one system fails, the entire system does not fail.
[src:dask/distributed-computing] Examples of distributed systems vary from SOA-based systems to microservices to massively multiplayer online games to peer-to-peer applications.
[src:dask/distributed-computing] Distributed systems cost more than monolithic architectures, primarily due to increased needs for additional hardware, servers, gateways, firewalls, new subnets, proxies, and so on.
[src:dask/distributed-computing] Distributed systems can also suffer from fallacies of distributed computing.
[src:dask/distributed-computing] Conversely, a well-designed distributed system is more scalable, more durable, more changeable, and more fine-tuned than a monolithic application deployed on a single machine.
[src:dask/distributed-computing] According to Marc Brooker: "a system is scalable in the range where marginal cost of additional workload is nearly constant." Serverless technologies fit this definition but the total cost of ownership, and not just the infrastructure cost must be considered.
[src:dask/distributed-computing] A computer program that runs within a distributed system is called a **distributed program**, and *distributed programming* is the process of writing such programs.
[src:dask/distributed-computing] There are many types of implementations for the message-passing mechanism, including pure HTTP, RPC-like connectors, and message queues.
[src:dask/distributed-computing] The word *distributed* in terms such as "distributed system", "distributed programming", and "distributed algorithm" originally referred to computer networks where individual computers were physically distributed within some geographical area.
[src:dask/distributed-computing] The terms are nowadays used in a much wider sense, even referring to autonomous processes that run on the same physical computer and interact with each other by message passing.
[src:dask/distributed-computing] A distributed system may have a common goal, such as solving a large computational problem; the user then perceives the collection of autonomous processors as a unit.
[src:dask/distributed-computing] Alternatively, each computer may have its own user with individual needs, and the purpose of the distributed system is to coordinate the use of shared resources or provide communication services to the users.
[src:dask/distributed-computing] In distributed systems, events represent a fact or state change (e.g., *OrderPlaced*) and are typically broadcast asynchronously to multiple consumers, promoting loose coupling and scalability.
[src:dask/distributed-computing] While events generally don't expect an immediate response, acknowledgment mechanisms are often implemented at the infrastructure level (e.g., Kafka commit offsets, SNS delivery statuses) rather than being an inherent part of the event pattern itself.
[src:dask/distributed-computing] In contrast, messages serve a broader role, encompassing commands (e.g., *ProcessPayment*), events (e.g., *PaymentProcessed*), and documents (e.g., *DataPayload*).
[src:dask/distributed-computing] Both events and messages can support various delivery guarantees, including at-least-once, at-most-once, and exactly-once, depending on the technology stack and implementation.
[src:dask/distributed-computing] However, exactly-once delivery is often achieved through idempotency mechanisms rather than true, infrastructure-level exactly-once semantics.
[src:dask/distributed-computing] Delivery patterns for both events and messages include publish/subscribe (one-to-many) and point-to-point (one-to-one).
[src:dask/distributed-computing] While request/reply is technically possible, it is more commonly associated with messaging patterns rather than pure event-driven systems.
[src:dask/distributed-computing] Events excel at state propagation and decoupled notifications, while messages are better suited for command execution, workflow orchestration, and explicit coordination.
[src:dask/distributed-computing] Modern architectures commonly combine both approaches, leveraging events for distributed state change notifications and messages for targeted command execution and structured workflows based on specific timing, ordering, and delivery requirements.
[src:dask/distributed-computing] Distributed systems are groups of networked computers which share a common goal for their work.
[src:dask/distributed-computing] The terms "concurrent computing", "parallel computing", and "distributed computing" have much overlap, and no clear distinction exists between them.
[src:dask/distributed-computing] The same system may be characterized both as "parallel" and "distributed"; the processors in a typical distributed system run concurrently in parallel.
[src:dask/distributed-computing] Parallel computing may be seen as a particularly tightly coupled form of distributed computing, and distributed computing may be seen as a loosely coupled form of parallel computing.
[src:dask/distributed-computing] The figure on the right illustrates the difference between distributed and parallel systems.
[src:dask/distributed-computing] Figure (a) is a schematic view of a typical distributed system; the system is represented as a network topology in which each node is a computer and each line connecting the nodes is a communication link.
[src:dask/distributed-computing] Figure (b) shows the same distributed system in more detail: each computer has its own local memory, and information can be exchanged only by passing messages from one node to another by using the available communication links.
[src:dask/distributed-computing] Figure (c) shows a parallel system in which each processor has a direct access to a shared memory.
[src:dask/distributed-computing] The situation is further complicated by the traditional uses of the terms parallel and distributed *algorithm* that do not quite match the above definitions of parallel and distributed *systems* (see below for more detailed discussion).
[src:dask/distributed-computing] Nevertheless, as a rule of thumb, high-performance parallel computation in a shared-memory multiprocessor uses parallel algorithms while the coordination of a large-scale distributed system uses distributed algorithms.
[src:dask/distributed-computing] The use of concurrent processes which communicate through message-passing has its roots in operating system architectures studied in the 1960s.
[src:dask/distributed-computing] The first widespread distributed systems were local-area networks such as Ethernet, which was invented in the 1970s.
[src:dask/distributed-computing] ARPANET, one of the predecessors of the Internet, was introduced in the late 1960s, and ARPANET e-mail was invented in the early 1970s.
[src:dask/distributed-computing] E-mail became the most successful application of ARPANET, and it is probably the earliest example of a large-scale distributed application.
[src:dask/distributed-computing] In addition to ARPANET (and its successor, the global Internet), other early worldwide computer networks included Usenet and FidoNet from the 1980s, both of which were used to support distributed discussion systems.
[src:dask/distributed-computing] The study of distributed computing became its own branch of computer science in the late 1970s and early 1980s.
[src:dask/distributed-computing] The first conference in the field, Symposium on Principles of Distributed Computing (PODC), dates back to 1982, and its counterpart International Symposium on Distributed Computing (DISC) was first held in Ottawa in 1985 as the International Workshop on Distributed Algorithms on Graphs.
[src:dask/distributed-computing] Various hardware and software architectures are used for distributed computing.
[src:dask/distributed-computing] At a lower level, it is necessary to interconnect multiple CPUs with some sort of network, regardless of whether that network is printed onto a circuit board or made up of loosely coupled devices and cables.
[src:dask/distributed-computing] At a higher level, it is necessary to interconnect processes running on those CPUs with some sort of communication system.
[src:dask/distributed-computing] Distributed programming typically falls into one of several basic architectures: client–server, three-tier, *n*-tier, or peer-to-peer; or categories: loose coupling, or tight coupling.
[src:dask/distributed-computing] Another basic aspect of distributed computing architecture is the method of communicating and coordinating work among concurrent processes.
[src:dask/distributed-computing] Through various message passing protocols, processes may communicate directly with one another, typically in a main/sub relationship.
[src:dask/distributed-computing] Alternatively, a "database-centric" architecture can enable distributed computing to be done without any form of direct inter-process communication, by utilizing a shared database.
[src:dask/distributed-computing] Database-centric architecture in particular provides relational processing analytics in a schematic architecture allowing for live environment relay.
[src:dask/distributed-computing] This enables distributed computing functions both within and beyond the parameters of a networked database.
[src:dask/distributed-computing] Cell-based architecture is a distributed computing approach in which computational resources are organized into self-contained units called cells.
[src:dask/distributed-computing] Each cell operates independently, processing requests while maintaining scalability, fault isolation, and availability.
[src:dask/distributed-computing] A cell typically consists of multiple services or application components and functions as an autonomous unit.
[src:dask/distributed-computing] Some implementations replicate entire sets of services across multiple cells, while others partition workloads between cells.
[src:dask/distributed-computing] In replicated models, requests may be rerouted to an operational cell if another experiences a failure.
[src:dask/distributed-computing] This design is intended to enhance system resilience by reducing the impact of localized failures.
[src:dask/distributed-computing] Some implementations employ circuit breakers within and between cells.
[src:dask/distributed-computing] Within a cell, circuit breakers may be used to prevent cascading failures among services, while inter-cell circuit breakers can isolate failing cells and redirect traffic to those that remain operational.
[src:dask/distributed-computing] Cell-based architecture has been adopted in some large-scale distributed systems, particularly in cloud-native and high-availability environments, where fault isolation and redundancy are key design considerations.
[src:dask/distributed-computing] Its implementation varies depending on system requirements, infrastructure constraints, and operational objectives.
[src:dask/distributed-computing] According to Reactive Manifesto, reactive distributed systems are responsive, resilient, elastic and message-driven.
[src:dask/distributed-computing] Subsequently, Reactive systems are more flexible, loosely-coupled and scalable.
[src:dask/distributed-computing] To make your systems reactive, you are advised to implement Reactive Principles.
[src:dask/distributed-computing] Reactive Principles are a set of principles and patterns which help to make your cloud native application as well as edge native applications more reactive.
[src:dask/distributed-computing] Many tasks that we would like to automate by using a computer are of question–answer type: we would like to ask a question and the computer should produce an answer.
[src:dask/distributed-computing] In theoretical computer science, such tasks are called computational problems.
[src:dask/distributed-computing] Formally, a computational problem consists of *instances* together with a *solution* for each instance.
[src:dask/distributed-computing] Instances are questions that we can ask, and solutions are desired answers to these questions.
[src:dask/distributed-computing] Theoretical computer science seeks to understand which computational problems can be solved by using a computer (computability theory) and how efficiently (computational complexity theory).
[src:dask/distributed-computing] Traditionally, it is said that a problem can be solved by using a computer if we can design an algorithm that produces a correct solution for any given instance.
[src:dask/distributed-computing] Such an algorithm can be implemented as a computer program that runs on a general-purpose computer: the program reads a problem instance from input, performs some computation, and produces the solution as output.
[src:dask/distributed-computing] Formalisms such as random-access machines or universal Turing machines can be used as abstract models of a sequential general-purpose computer executing such an algorithm.
[src:dask/distributed-computing] The field of concurrent and distributed computing studies similar questions in the case of either multiple computers, or a computer that executes a network of interacting processes: which computational problems can be solved in such a network and how efficiently?
[src:dask/distributed-computing] However, it is not at all obvious what is meant by "solving a problem" in the case of a concurrent or distributed system: for example, what is the task of the algorithm designer, and what is the concurrent or distributed equivalent of a sequential general-purpose computer?
[src:dask/distributed-computing] The discussion below focuses on the case of multiple computers, although many of the issues are the same for concurrent processes running on a single computer.
[src:dask/distributed-computing] In the case of distributed algorithms, computational problems are typically related to graphs.
[src:dask/distributed-computing] Often the graph that describes the structure of the computer network *is* the problem instance.
[src:dask/distributed-computing] This is illustrated in the following example.
[src:dask/distributed-computing] Consider the computational problem of finding a coloring of a given graph *G*.
[src:dask/distributed-computing] While the field of parallel algorithms has a different focus than the field of distributed algorithms, there is much interaction between the two fields.
[src:dask/distributed-computing] For example, the Cole–Vishkin algorithm for graph coloring was originally presented as a parallel algorithm, but the same technique can also be used directly as a distributed algorithm.
[src:dask/distributed-computing] Moreover, a parallel algorithm can be implemented either in a parallel system (using shared memory) or in a distributed system (using message passing).
[src:dask/distributed-computing] The traditional boundary between parallel and distributed algorithms (choose a suitable network vs. run in any given network) does not lie in the same place as the boundary between parallel and distributed systems (shared memory vs. message passing).
[src:dask/distributed-computing] In parallel algorithms, yet another resource in addition to time and space is the number of computers.
[src:dask/distributed-computing] Indeed, often there is a trade-off between the running time and the number of computers: the problem can be solved faster if there are more computers running in parallel (see speedup).
[src:dask/distributed-computing] If a decision problem can be solved in polylogarithmic time by using a polynomial number of processors, then the problem is said to be in the class NC.
[src:dask/distributed-computing] The class NC can be defined equally well by using the PRAM formalism or Boolean circuits—PRAM machines can simulate Boolean circuits efficiently and vice versa.
[src:dask/distributed-computing] In the analysis of distributed algorithms, more attention is usually paid on communication operations than computational steps.
[src:dask/distributed-computing] Perhaps the simplest model of distributed computing is a synchronous system where all nodes operate in a lockstep fashion.
[src:dask/distributed-computing] This model is commonly known as the LOCAL model.
[src:dask/distributed-computing] During each *communication round*, all nodes in parallel (1) receive the latest messages from their neighbours, (2) perform arbitrary local computation, and (3) send new messages to their neighbors.
[src:dask/distributed-computing] In such systems, a central complexity measure is the number of synchronous communication rounds required to complete the task.
[src:dask/distributed-computing] This complexity measure is closely related to the diameter of the network.
[src:dask/distributed-computing] On the one hand, any computable problem can be solved trivially in a synchronous distributed system in approximately 2*D* communication rounds: simply gather all information in one location (*D* rounds), solve the problem, and inform each node about the solution (*D* rounds).
[src:dask/distributed-computing] On the other hand, if the running time of the algorithm is much smaller than *D* communication rounds, then the nodes in the network must produce their output without having the possibility to obtain information about distant parts of the network.
[src:dask/distributed-computing] In other words, the nodes must make globally consistent decisions based on information that is available in their *local D-neighbourhood*.
[src:dask/distributed-computing] Many distributed algorithms are known with the running time much smaller than *D* rounds, and understanding which problems can be solved by such algorithms is one of the central research questions of the field.
[src:dask/distributed-computing] Typically an algorithm which solves a problem in polylogarithmic time in the network size is considered efficient in this model.
[src:dask/distributed-computing] Another commonly used measure is the total number of bits transmitted in the network (cf. communication complexity).
[src:dask/distributed-computing] The features of this concept are typically captured with the CONGEST(B) model, which is similarly defined as the LOCAL model, but where single messages can only contain B bits.
[src:dask/distributed-computing] Traditional computational problems take the perspective that the user asks a question, a computer (or a distributed system) processes the question, then produces an answer and stops.
[src:dask/distributed-computing] However, there are also problems where the system is required not to stop, including the dining philosophers problem and other similar mutual exclusion problems.
[src:dask/distributed-computing] In these problems, the distributed system is supposed to continuously coordinate the use of shared resources so that no conflicts or deadlocks occur.
[src:dask/distributed-computing] There are also fundamental challenges that are unique to distributed computing, for example those related to *fault-tolerance*.
[src:dask/distributed-computing] Examples of related problems include consensus problems, Byzantine fault tolerance, and self-stabilisation.
[src:dask/distributed-computing] Note that in distributed systems, latency should be measured through "99th percentile" because "median" and "average" can be misleading.
[src:dask/distributed-computing] The network nodes communicate among themselves in order to decide which of them will get into the "coordinator" state.
[src:dask/distributed-computing] For that, they need some method in order to break the symmetry among them.
[src:dask/distributed-computing] For example, if each node has unique and comparable identities, then the nodes can compare their identities, and decide that the node with the highest identity is the coordinator.
[src:dask/distributed-computing] The definition of this problem is often attributed to LeLann, who formalized it as a method to create a new token in a token ring network in which the token has been lost.
[src:dask/distributed-computing] Coordinator election algorithms are designed to be economical in terms of total bytes transmitted, and time.
[src:dask/distributed-computing] The algorithm suggested by Gallager, Humblet, and Spira for general undirected graphs has had a strong impact on the design of distributed algorithms in general, and won the Dijkstra Prize for an influential paper in distributed computing.
[src:dask/distributed-computing] Many other algorithms were suggested for different kinds of network graphs, such as undirected rings, unidirectional rings, complete graphs, grids, directed Euler graphs, and others.
[src:dask/distributed-computing] A general method that decouples the issue of the graph family from the design of the coordinator election algorithm was suggested by Korach, Kutten, and Moran.
[src:dask/distributed-computing] In order to perform coordination, distributed systems employ the concept of coordinators.
[src:dask/distributed-computing] The coordinator election problem is to choose a process from among a group of processes on different processors in a distributed system to act as the central coordinator.
[src:dask/distributed-computing] Several central coordinator election algorithms exist.
[src:dask/distributed-computing] So far the focus has been on *designing* a distributed system that solves a given problem.
[src:dask/distributed-computing] A complementary research problem is *studying* the properties of a given distributed system.
[src:dask/distributed-computing] The halting problem is an analogous example from the field of centralised computation: we are given a computer program and the task is to decide whether it halts or runs forever.
[src:dask/distributed-computing] The halting problem is undecidable in the general case, and naturally understanding the behaviour of a computer network is at least as hard as understanding the behaviour of one computer.
[src:dask/distributed-computing] However, there are many interesting special cases that are decidable.
[src:dask/distributed-computing] In particular, it is possible to reason about the behaviour of a network of finite-state machines.
[src:dask/distributed-computing] One example is telling whether a given network of interacting (asynchronous and non-deterministic) finite-state machines can reach a deadlock.
[src:dask/distributed-computing] This problem is PSPACE-complete, i.e., it is decidable, but not likely that there is an efficient (centralised, parallel or distributed) algorithm that solves the problem in the case of large networks.
[src:dask/pandas-software] The development of Pandas introduced into Python many comparable features of working with DataFrames that were established in the R programming language.
[src:dask/pandas-software] The library is built upon another library, NumPy.
[src:dask/pandas-software] Developer Wes McKinney started working on Pandas in 2008 while at AQR Capital Management out of the need for a high performance, flexible tool to perform quantitative analysis on financial data.
[src:dask/pandas-software] Before leaving AQR, he was able to convince management to allow him to open source the library in 2009.
[src:dask/pandas-software] Another AQR employee, Chang She, joined the effort in 2012 as the second major contributor to the library.
[src:dask/pandas-software] In 2015, Pandas signed on as a fiscally sponsored project of NumFOCUS, a 501(c)(3) nonprofit charity in the United States.
[src:dask/pandas-software] Pandas is built around data structures called *Series* and *DataFrames*.
[src:dask/pandas-software] Data for these collections can be imported from various file formats such as comma-separated values, JSON, Parquet, SQL database tables or queries, and Microsoft Excel.
[src:dask/pandas-software] A *Series* is a one-dimensional array-like object that stores a sequence of values together with an associated set of labels, called an index.
[src:dask/pandas-software] It is built on top of NumPy's array and affords many similar functionalities, but instead of using implicit integer positions, a Series allows explicit index labels of many data types.
[src:dask/pandas-software] A Series can be created from Python lists, dictionaries, or NumPy arrays.
[src:dask/pandas-software] If no index is provided, pandas automatically assigns a default integer index ranging from 0 to n-1, where n is the number of items in the Series.
[src:dask/pandas-software] Series can be used arithmetically, as in the statement `series_3 = series_1 + series_2`.
[src:dask/pandas-software] This will align data points with corresponding index values in `series_1` and `series_2` (similar to a join in relational algebra), then add them together to produce new values in `series_3`.
[src:dask/pandas-software] A Series has various attributes, such as `name` (Series name), `dtype` (data type of values), `shape` (number of rows), `values`, and `index`.
[src:dask/pandas-software] They can be used in many of the same operations as NumPy arrays, with additional methods for reindexing, label-based selection, and handling missing data.
[src:dask/pandas-software] A *DataFrame* is a two-dimensional, tabular data structure with labeled rows and columns.
[src:dask/pandas-software] Each column is stored internally as a Series and may hold a different data type (numeric, string, boolean, etc.).
[src:dask/pandas-software] To retrieve a DataFrame column as a Series, use either 1) the index (dict-like notation) or 2) the name of column if the name is a valid Python identifier (attribute-like access).
[src:dask/pandas-software] DataFrames support operations such as column assignment, row and column deletion, label-based indexing with `loc`, position-based indexing with `iloc`, reshaping, grouping, and joining.
[src:dask/pandas-software] Merge operations implement a subset of relational algebra and allow one-to-one, many-to-one, and many-to-many joins.
[src:dask/pandas-software] pandas' syntax for mapping index values to relevant data is the same syntax Python uses to map dictionary keys to values.
[src:dask/pandas-software] For example, if `s` is a Series, `s['a']` will return the data point at index `a`.
[src:dask/pandas-software] Unlike dictionary keys, index values are not guaranteed to be unique.
[src:dask/pandas-software] If a Series uses the index value `a` for multiple data points, then `s['a']` will instead return a new Series containing all matching values.
[src:dask/pandas-software] A DataFrame's column names are stored and implemented identically to an index.
[src:dask/pandas-software] As such, a DataFrame can be thought of as having two indices: one column-based and one row-based.
[src:dask/pandas-software] Because column names are stored as an index, these are not required to be unique.
[src:dask/pandas-software] If `data` is a Series, then `data['a']` returns all values with the index value of `a`.
[src:dask/pandas-software] However, if `data` is a DataFrame, then `data['a']` returns all values in the column(s) named `a`.
[src:dask/pandas-software] To avoid this ambiguity, Pandas supports the syntax `data.loc['a']` as an alternative way to filter using the index.
[src:dask/pandas-software] Pandas also supports the syntax `data.iloc[n]`, which always takes an integer *n* and returns the *nth* value, counting from 0.
[src:dask/pandas-software] This allows a user to act as though the index is an array-like sequence of integers, regardless of how it is actually defined.
[src:dask/pandas-software] pandas also supports hierarchical indices with multiple values per data point through the "MultiIndex" class.
[src:dask/pandas-software] MultiIndex objects allow a single DataFrame to represent multiple dimensions, similar to a pivot table in Microsoft Excel, where each level can optionally carry its own unique name.
[src:dask/pandas-software] In practice, data with more than 2 dimensions is often represented using DataFrames with hierarchical indices, instead of the higher-dimension *Panel* and *Panel4D* data structures.
[src:dask/pandas-software] pandas supports a variety of indexing and subsetting techniques, allowing data to be selected by label, index, or Boolean conditions.
[src:dask/pandas-software] For example, `df[df['col1'] > 5]` will return all rows in the DataFrame `df` for which the value of the column `col1` exceeds 5.
[src:dask/pandas-software] The library also implements grouping operations based on the split-apply-combine approach, enabling users to aggregate, transform, or restructure data according to column values or functions applied to index labels.
[src:dask/pandas-software] For example, `df['col1'].groupby(df['col2'])` groups the data in 'col1' by their values in 'col2', while `df.groupby(lambda i: i % 2)` groups all data in the whole DataFrame by whether their index is even.
[src:dask/pandas-software] The library also provides extensive tools for transforming, filtering and summarizing data.
[src:dask/pandas-software] Users may apply arbitrary functions to Series and DataFrames, and because the library is built on top of Numpy, most NumPy functions can be applied directly to pandas objects as well.
[src:dask/pandas-software] The library also includes built-in operations for arithmetic operations, string processing, and descriptive statistics such as mean, median, and standard deviation.
[src:dask/pandas-software] These built-in functions are designed to handle missing data, usually represented by the floating-point value NaN.
[src:dask/pandas-software] In addition, pandas includes tools for reorganizing data into different structural formats, with methods that can reshape tabular data between "wide" and "long" formats and pivot values based on column labels. pandas also implements a flexible set of relational operations for combining datasets.
[src:dask/pandas-software] For instance, `merge()` links row in DataFrames based on one or more shared keys or indices, supporting one-to-one, one-to-many, and many-to-many relationships in a manner analogous to join operations in relational databases like SQL.
[src:dask/pandas-software] DataFrames can also be concatenated or stacked together along an axis through the `concat()` method, and overlapping data can be further spliced together using `combine_first()` to fill in missing values.
[src:dask/pandas-software] Furthermore, the library includes specialized support for working with time-series data.
[src:dask/pandas-software] Features include the ability to interpolate values and filter using a range of timestamps, such as `data['1/1/2023':'2/2/2023']` , which will return all dates between January 1 and February 2.
[src:dask/pandas-software] Missing values in time-series data are represented by a dedicated NaT (Not a Timestamp) object, instead of the NaN value it uses elsewhere.
[src:dask/pandas-software] Pandas has been criticized for its inefficiency.
[src:dask/pandas-software] The entire dataset must be loaded in RAM, and the library does not optimize query plans or support parallel computing across multiple cores.
[src:dask/pandas-software] Wes McKinney, the creator of Pandas, has recommended Apache Arrow as an alternative to address these performance concerns and other limitations.
[src:dask/pandas-software] Otherwise, he says, "my rule of thumb for pandas is that you should have 5 to 10 times as much RAM as the size of your dataset".
[src:dask/pandas-software] Sort foods by calories (descending order):df.sort_values("calories", ascending=False) Note: Any missing values are automatically sorted to the end of the Series.
[src:dask/pandas-software] Group items by category and calculate average macros:df.groupby("category")[["carb_g", "fat_g", "protein_g"]].mean() This returns a GroupBy object that is analogous to a collection of DataFrames.
[src:dask/pandas-software] Find the highest-calorie food per category:df.loc[df.groupby("category")["protein_g"].idxmax()] `idxmax()` returns the index value of the maximum value.
[src:dask/pandas-software] `idxmin()` performs an analogous function with the minimum value.
[src:dask/pandas-software] Handle missing data:df.loc[2, "fiber_g"] = None # Simulate a missing value df["fiber_g"].fillna(df["fiber_g"].mean()) This replaces the `None` value with `NaN`.
[src:dask/pandas-software] Alternatively, we can also drop rows containing missing values by calling `df.dropna()`.
[src:dask/pandas-software] To merge datasets with different key column names, use the parameters `left_on` and `right_on` instead.
[src:dask/pandas-software] Categorize food by calories:df["calorie_level"] = pd.cut( df["calories"], bins=[0,100,200,300], labels=["Low", "Medium", "High"] ) This splits numeric data into separate "bins" or intervals, thereby allowing continuous measurements to be analyzed as discrete categories.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] In computer science, **parallelism** and concurrency are two different things: a parallel program uses multiple CPU cores, each core performing a task independently.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] On the other hand, concurrency enables a program to deal with multiple tasks even on a single CPU core; the core switches between tasks (i.e. threads) without necessarily completing each one.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] A program can have both, neither or a combination of parallelism and concurrency characteristics.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] Parallel computers can be roughly classified according to the level at which the hardware supports parallelism, with multi-core and multi-processor computers having multiple processing elements within a single machine, while clusters, MPPs, and grids use multiple computers to work on the same task.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] Specialized parallel computer architectures are sometimes used alongside traditional processors, for accelerating specific tasks.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] Communication and synchronization between the different subtasks are typically some of the greatest obstacles to getting optimal parallel program performance.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] A theoretical upper bound on the speed-up of a single program as a result of parallelization is given by Amdahl's law, which states that it is limited by the fraction of time for which the parallelization can be utilised.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] Traditionally, computer software has been written for serial computation.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] To solve a problem, an algorithm is constructed and implemented as a serial stream of instructions.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] These instructions are executed on a central processing unit on one computer.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] Only one instruction may execute at a time—after that instruction is finished, the next one is executed.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] Parallel computing, on the other hand, uses multiple processing elements simultaneously to solve a problem.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] This is accomplished by breaking the problem into independent parts so that each processing element can execute its part of the algorithm simultaneously with the others.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] The processing elements can be diverse and include resources such as a single computer with multiple processors, several networked computers, specialized hardware, or any combination of the above.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] Historically parallel computing was used for scientific computing and the simulation of scientific problems, particularly in the natural and engineering sciences, such as meteorology.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] This led to the design of parallel hardware and software, and high performance computing.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] Frequency scaling was the dominant reason for improvements in computer performance from the mid-1980s until 2004.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] The runtime of a program is equal to the number of instructions multiplied by the average time per instruction.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] Maintaining everything else constant, increasing the clock frequency decreases the average time it takes to execute an instruction.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] An increase in frequency thus decreases runtime for all compute-bound programs.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] However, power consumption *P* by a chip is given by the equation *P* = *C* × *V* 2 × *F*, where *C* is the capacitance being switched per clock cycle (proportional to the number of transistors whose inputs change), *V* is voltage, and *F* is the processor frequency (cycles per second).
[src:dask/parallel-computing] Increases in frequency increase the amount of power used in a processor.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] Increasing processor power consumption led ultimately to Intel's May 8, 2004 cancellation of its Tejas and Jayhawk processors, which is generally cited as the end of frequency scaling as the dominant computer architecture paradigm.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] To deal with the problem of power consumption and overheating the major central processing unit (CPU or processor) manufacturers started to produce power efficient processors with multiple cores.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] The core is the computing unit of the processor and in multi-core processors each core is independent and can access the same memory concurrently.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] Multi-core processors have brought parallel computing to desktop computers.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] Thus parallelization of serial programs has become a mainstream programming task.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] In 2012 quad-core processors became standard for desktop computers, while servers had 10+ core processors.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] Moore's law predicted that the number of cores per processor would double every 18–24 months.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] By 2023 some processors had over one hundred cores.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] Some designs having a mix of performance and efficiency cores (such as ARM's big.LITTLE design) due to thermal and design constraints.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] An operating system can ensure that different tasks and user programs are run in parallel on the available cores.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] However, for a serial software program to take full advantage of the multi-core architecture the programmer needs to restructure and parallelize the code.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] A speed-up of application software runtime will no longer be achieved through frequency scaling, instead programmers will need to parallelize their software code to take advantage of the increasing computing power of multicore architectures.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] Optimally, the speedup from parallelization would be linear—doubling the number of processing elements should halve the runtime, and doubling it a second time should again halve the runtime.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] However, very few parallel algorithms achieve optimal speedup.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] Most of them have a near-linear speedup for small numbers of processing elements, which flattens out into a constant value for large numbers of processing elements.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] The maximum potential speedup of an overall system can be calculated by Amdahl's law.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] Amdahl's Law indicates that optimal performance improvement is achieved by balancing enhancements to both parallelizable and non-parallelizable components of a task.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] Furthermore, it reveals that increasing the number of processors yields diminishing returns, with negligible speedup gains beyond a certain point.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] Amdahl's Law has limitations, including assumptions of fixed workload, neglecting inter-process communication and synchronization overheads, primarily focusing on computational aspect and ignoring extrinsic factors such as data persistence, I/O operations, and memory access overheads.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] Gustafson's law and Universal Scalability Law give a more realistic assessment of the parallel performance.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] Understanding data dependencies is fundamental in implementing parallel algorithms.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] No program can run more quickly than the longest chain of dependent calculations (known as the critical path), since calculations that depend upon prior calculations in the chain must be executed in order.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] However, most algorithms do not consist of just a long chain of dependent calculations; there are usually opportunities to execute independent calculations in parallel.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] Let *P**i* and *P**j* be two program segments.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] Bernstein's conditions describe when the two are independent and can be executed in parallel.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] For *P**i*, let *I**i* be all of the input variables and *O**i* the output variables, and likewise for *P**j*.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] Violation of the first condition introduces a flow dependency, corresponding to the first segment producing a result used by the second segment.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] The second condition represents an anti-dependency, when the second segment produces a variable needed by the first segment.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] The third and final condition represents an output dependency: when two segments write to the same location, the result comes from the logically last executed segment.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] In this example, instruction 3 cannot be executed before (or even in parallel with) instruction 2, because instruction 3 uses a result from instruction 2.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] It violates condition 1, and thus introduces a flow dependency.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] In this example, there are no dependencies between the instructions, so they can all be run in parallel.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] Bernstein's conditions do not allow memory to be shared between different processes.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] For that, some means of enforcing an ordering between accesses is necessary, such as semaphores, barriers or some other synchronization method.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] Subtasks in a parallel program are often called threads.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] Some parallel computer architectures use smaller, lightweight versions of threads known as fibers, while others use bigger versions known as processes.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] However, "threads" is generally accepted as a generic term for subtasks.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] Threads will often need synchronized access to an object or other resource, for example when they must update a variable that is shared between them.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] Without synchronization, the instructions between the two threads may be interleaved in any order.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] If instruction 1B is executed between 1A and 3A, or if instruction 1A is executed between 1B and 3B, the program will produce incorrect data.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] The programmer must use a lock to provide mutual exclusion.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] A lock is a programming language construct that allows one thread to take control of a variable and prevent other threads from reading or writing it, until that variable is unlocked.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] The thread holding the lock is free to execute its critical section (the section of a program that requires exclusive access to some variable), and to unlock the data when it is finished.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] One thread will successfully lock variable V, while the other thread will be locked out—unable to proceed until V is unlocked again.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] This guarantees correct execution of the program.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] Locks may be necessary to ensure correct program execution when threads must serialize access to resources, but their use can greatly slow a program and may affect its reliability.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] Locking multiple variables using non-atomic locks introduces the possibility of program deadlock.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] An atomic lock locks multiple variables all at once.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] If it cannot lock all of them, it does not lock any of them.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] If two threads each need to lock the same two variables using non-atomic locks, it is possible that one thread will lock one of them and the second thread will lock the second variable.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] In such a case, neither thread can complete, and deadlock results.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] Many parallel programs require that their subtasks act in synchrony.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] Barriers are typically implemented using a lock or a semaphore.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] One class of algorithms, known as lock-free and wait-free algorithms, altogether avoids the use of locks and barriers.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] However, this approach is generally difficult to implement and requires correctly designed data structures.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] Not all parallelization results in speed-up.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] Generally, as a task is split up into more and more threads, those threads spend an ever-increasing portion of their time communicating with each other or waiting on each other for access to resources.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] Once the overhead from resource contention or communication dominates the time spent on other computation, further parallelization (that is, splitting the workload over even more threads) increases rather than decreases the amount of time required to finish.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] This problem, known as parallel slowdown, can be improved in some cases by software analysis and redesign.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] Applications are often classified according to how often their subtasks need to synchronize or communicate with each other.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] An application exhibits fine-grained parallelism if its subtasks must communicate many times per second; it exhibits coarse-grained parallelism if they do not communicate many times per second, and it exhibits embarrassing parallelism if they rarely or never have to communicate.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] Embarrassingly parallel applications are considered the easiest to parallelize.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] Flynn created one of the earliest classification systems for parallel (and sequential) computers and programs, now known as Flynn's taxonomy.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] Flynn classified programs and computers by whether they were operating using a single set or multiple sets of instructions, and whether or not those instructions were using a single set or multiple sets of data.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] The single-instruction-single-data (SISD) classification is equivalent to an entirely sequential program.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] The single-instruction-multiple-data (SIMD) classification is analogous to doing the same operation repeatedly over a large data set.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] This is commonly done in signal processing applications.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] Multiple-instruction-single-data (MISD) is a rarely used classification.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] While computer architectures to deal with this were devised (such as systolic arrays), few applications that fit this class materialized.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] Multiple-instruction-multiple-data (MIMD) programs are by far the most common type of parallel programs.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] Hennessy, "Some machines are hybrids of these categories, of course, but this classic model has survived because it is simple, easy to understand, and gives a good first approximation.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] Parallel computing can incur significant overhead in practice, primarily due to the costs associated with merging data from multiple processes.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] Specifically, inter-process communication and synchronization can lead to overheads that are substantially higher—often by two or more orders of magnitude—compared to processing the same data on a single thread.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] Therefore, the overall improvement should be carefully evaluated.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] From the advent of very-large-scale integration (VLSI) computer-chip fabrication technology in the 1970s until about 1986, speed-up in computer architecture was driven by doubling computer word size—the amount of information the processor can manipulate per cycle.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] Increasing the word size reduces the number of instructions the processor must execute to perform an operation on variables whose sizes are greater than the length of the word.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] Historically, 4-bit microprocessors were replaced with 8-bit, then 16-bit, then 32-bit microprocessors.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] This trend generally came to an end with the introduction of 32-bit processors, which has been a standard in general-purpose computing for two decades.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] Not until the early 2000s, with the advent of x86-64 architectures, did 64-bit processors become commonplace.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] A computer program is, in essence, a stream of instructions executed by a processor.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] Without instruction-level parallelism, a processor can only issue less than one instruction per clock cycle (IPC < 1).
[src:dask/parallel-computing] These processors are known as *subscalar* processors.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] These instructions can be re-ordered and combined into groups which are then executed in parallel without changing the result of the program.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] This is known as instruction-level parallelism.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] Advances in instruction-level parallelism dominated computer architecture from the mid-1980s until the mid-1990s.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] All modern processors have multi-stage instruction pipelines.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] Each stage in the pipeline corresponds to a different action the processor performs on that instruction in that stage; a processor with an *N*-stage pipeline can have up to *N* different instructions at different stages of completion and thus can issue one instruction per clock cycle (IPC = 1).
[src:dask/parallel-computing] These processors are known as *scalar* processors.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] The canonical example of a pipelined processor is a RISC processor, with five stages: instruction fetch (IF), instruction decode (ID), execute (EX), memory access (MEM), and register write back (WB).
[src:dask/parallel-computing] The Pentium 4 processor had a 35-stage pipeline.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] Most modern processors also have multiple execution units.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] They usually combine this feature with pipelining and thus can issue more than one instruction per clock cycle (IPC > 1).
[src:dask/parallel-computing] These processors are known as *superscalar* processors.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] Superscalar processors differ from multi-core processors in that the several execution units are not entire processors (i.e. processing units).
[src:dask/parallel-computing] Instructions can be grouped together only if there is no data dependency between them.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] Scoreboarding and the Tomasulo algorithm (which is similar to scoreboarding but makes use of register renaming) are two of the most common techniques for implementing out-of-order execution and instruction-level parallelism.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] Task parallelisms is the characteristic of a parallel program that "entirely different calculations can be performed on either the same or different sets of data".
[src:dask/parallel-computing] This contrasts with data parallelism, where the same calculation is performed on the same or different sets of data.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] Task parallelism involves the decomposition of a task into sub-tasks and then allocating each sub-task to a processor for execution.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] The processors would then execute these sub-tasks concurrently and often cooperatively.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] Task parallelism does not usually scale with the size of a problem.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] Superword level parallelism is a vectorization technique based on loop unrolling and basic block vectorization.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] It is distinct from loop vectorization algorithms in that it can exploit parallelism of inline code, such as manipulating coordinates, color channels or in loops unrolled by hand.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] Main memory in a parallel computer is either shared memory (shared between all processing elements in a single address space), or distributed memory (in which each processing element has its own local address space).
[src:dask/parallel-computing] Distributed memory refers to the fact that the memory is logically distributed, but often implies that it is physically distributed as well.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] Distributed shared memory and memory virtualization combine the two approaches, where the processing element has its own local memory and access to the memory on non-local processors.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] Accesses to local memory are typically faster than accesses to non-local memory.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] On the supercomputers, distributed shared memory space can be implemented using the programming model such as PGAS.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] This model allows processes on one compute node to transparently access the remote memory of another compute node.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] All compute nodes are also connected to an external shared memory system via high-speed interconnect, such as Infiniband, this external shared memory system is known as burst buffer, which is typically built from arrays of non-volatile memory physically distributed across multiple I/O nodes.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] Computer architectures in which each element of main memory can be accessed with equal latency and bandwidth are known as uniform memory access (UMA) systems.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] Typically, that can be achieved only by a shared memory system, in which the memory is not physically distributed.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] A system that does not have this property is known as a non-uniform memory access (NUMA) architecture.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] Distributed memory systems have non-uniform memory access.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] Computer systems (with the exception of Groq's LPUs) make use of caches—small and fast memories located close to the processor which store temporary copies of memory values (nearby in both the physical and logical sense).
[src:dask/parallel-computing] Parallel computer systems have difficulties with caches that may store the same value in more than one location, with the possibility of incorrect program execution.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] These computers require a cache coherency system, which keeps track of cached values and strategically purges them, thus ensuring correct program execution.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] Bus snooping is one of the most common methods for keeping track of which values are being accessed (and thus should be purged).
[src:dask/parallel-computing] Designing large, high-performance cache coherence systems is a very difficult problem in computer architecture.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] As a result, shared memory computer architectures do not scale and distributed memory systems do.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] Parallel computers based on interconnected networks need to have some kind of routing to enable the passing of messages between nodes that are not directly connected.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] The medium used for communication between the processors is likely to be hierarchical in large multiprocessor machines.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] Parallel computers can be roughly classified according to the level at which the hardware supports parallelism.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] This classification is broadly analogous to the distance between basic computing nodes.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] These are not mutually exclusive; for example, clusters of symmetric multiprocessors are relatively common.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] A multi-core processor is a processor that includes multiple processing units (called "cores") on the same chip.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] IBM's Cell microprocessor, designed for use in the Sony PlayStation 3, is a prominent multi-core processor.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] Each core in a multi-core processor can potentially be superscalar as well—that is, on every clock cycle, each core can issue multiple instructions from one thread.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] Simultaneous multithreading (of which Intel's Hyper-Threading is the best known) was an early form of pseudo-multi-coreism.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] A processor capable of concurrent multithreading includes multiple execution units in the same processing unit—that is it has a superscalar architecture—and can issue multiple instructions per clock cycle from *multiple* threads.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] Temporal multithreading on the other hand includes a single execution unit in the same processing unit and can issue one instruction at a time from *multiple* threads.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] A symmetric multiprocessor (SMP) is a computer system with multiple identical processors that share memory and connect via a bus.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] Bus contention prevents bus architectures from scaling.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] As a result, SMPs generally do not comprise more than 32 processors.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] Because of the small size of the processors and the significant reduction in the requirements for bus bandwidth achieved by large caches, such symmetric multiprocessors are extremely cost-effective, provided that a sufficient amount of memory bandwidth exists.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] A distributed computer (also known as a distributed memory multiprocessor) is a distributed memory computer system in which the processing elements are connected by a network.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] Distributed computers are highly scalable.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] The terms "concurrent computing", "parallel computing", and "distributed computing" have a lot of overlap, and no clear distinction exists between them.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] A cluster is a group of loosely coupled computers that work together closely, so that in some respects they can be regarded as a single computer.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] Clusters are composed of multiple standalone machines connected by a network.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] While machines in a cluster do not have to be symmetric, load balancing is more difficult if they are not.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] The most common type of cluster is the Beowulf cluster, which is a cluster implemented on multiple identical commercial off-the-shelf computers connected with a TCP/IP Ethernet local area network.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] Beowulf technology was originally developed by Thomas Sterling and Donald Becker.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] 87% of all Top500 supercomputers are clusters.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] The remaining are Massively Parallel Processors, explained below.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] Because grid computing systems (described below) can easily handle embarrassingly parallel problems, modern clusters are typically designed to handle more difficult problems—problems that require nodes to share intermediate results with each other more often.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] This requires a high bandwidth and, more importantly, a low-latency interconnection network.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] Many historic and current supercomputers use customized high-performance network hardware specifically designed for cluster computing, such as the Cray Gemini network.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] As of 2014, most current supercomputers use some off-the-shelf standard network hardware, often Myrinet, InfiniBand, or Gigabit Ethernet.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] A massively parallel processor (MPP) is a single computer with many networked processors.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] MPPs have many of the same characteristics as clusters, but MPPs have specialized interconnect networks (whereas clusters use commodity hardware for networking).
[src:dask/parallel-computing] MPPs also tend to be larger than clusters, typically having "far more" than 100 processors.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] In an MPP, "each CPU contains its own memory and copy of the operating system and application.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] IBM's Blue Gene/L, the fifth fastest supercomputer in the world according to the June 2009 TOP500 ranking, is an MPP.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] Grid computing is the most distributed form of parallel computing.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] It makes use of computers communicating over the Internet to work on a given problem.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] Because of the low bandwidth and extremely high latency available on the Internet, distributed computing typically deals only with embarrassingly parallel problems.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] Most grid computing applications use middleware (software that sits between the operating system and the application to manage network resources and standardize the software interface).
[src:dask/parallel-computing] The most common grid computing middleware is the Berkeley Open Infrastructure for Network Computing (BOINC).
[src:dask/parallel-computing] Often volunteer computing software makes use of "spare cycles", performing computations at times when a computer is idling.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] The ubiquity of the Internet and high-bandwidth networks enabled cloud computing, a model where massively parallel resources are provided as a service.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] This paradigm abstracts the underlying hardware, allowing users to access virtualized clusters for scalable workloads without managing physical infrastructure.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] Modern distributed ledger protocols apply parallel computing principles to overcome the sequential bottlenecks of traditional blockchains.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] By sharding the state space, newer consensus architectures allow for "massively parallel transaction processing".
[src:dask/parallel-computing] In this model, utilized by protocols such as Cerberus, independent transactions are treated as parallel tasks that can be executed simultaneously on different nodes, rather than being processed serially in a single global block.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] Within parallel computing, there are specialized parallel devices that remain niche areas of interest.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] While not domain-specific, they tend to be applicable to only a few classes of parallel problems.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] Reconfigurable computing is the use of a field-programmable gate array (FPGA) as a co-processor to a general-purpose computer.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] An FPGA is, in essence, a computer chip that can rewire itself for a given task.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] FPGAs can be programmed with hardware description languages such as VHDL or Verilog.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] Several vendors have created C to HDL languages that attempt to emulate the syntax and semantics of the C programming language, with which most programmers are familiar.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] The best known C to HDL languages are Mitrion-C, Impulse C, and Handel-C.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] Specific subsets of SystemC based on C++ can also be used for this purpose.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] AMD's decision to open its HyperTransport technology to third-party vendors has become the enabling technology for high-performance reconfigurable computing.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] General-purpose computing on graphics processing units (GPGPU) is a fairly recent trend in computer engineering research.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] GPUs are co-processors that have been heavily optimized for computer graphics processing.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] Computer graphics processing is a field dominated by data parallel operations—particularly linear algebra matrix operations.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] In the early days, GPGPU programs used the normal graphics APIs for executing programs.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] However, several new programming languages and platforms have been built to do general purpose computation on GPUs with both Nvidia and AMD releasing programming environments with CUDA and Stream SDK respectively.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] Other GPU programming languages include BrookGPU, PeakStream, and RapidMind.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] Nvidia has also released specific products for computation in their Tesla series.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] The technology consortium Khronos Group has released the OpenCL specification, which is a framework for writing programs that execute across platforms consisting of CPUs and GPUs.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] AMD, Apple, Intel, Nvidia and others are supporting OpenCL.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] Several application-specific integrated circuit (ASIC) approaches have been devised for dealing with parallel applications.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] Because an ASIC is (by definition) specific to a given application, it can be fully optimized for that application.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] As a result, for a given application, an ASIC tends to outperform a general-purpose computer.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] However, ASICs are created by UV photolithography.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] This process requires a mask set, which can be extremely expensive.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] A mask set can cost over a million US dollars.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] (The smaller the transistors required for the chip, the more expensive the mask will be.) Meanwhile, performance increases in general-purpose computing over time (as described by Moore's law) tend to wipe out these gains in only one or two chip generations.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] High initial cost, and the tendency to be overtaken by Moore's-law-driven general-purpose computing, has rendered ASICs unfeasible for most parallel computing applications.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] One example is the PFLOPS RIKEN MDGRAPE-3 machine which uses custom ASICs for molecular dynamics simulation.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] A vector processor is a CPU or computer system that can execute the same instruction on large sets of data.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] Vector processors have high-level operations that work on linear arrays of numbers or vectors.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] An example vector operation is *A* = *B* × *C*, where *A*, *B*, and *C* are each 64-element vectors of 64-bit floating-point numbers.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] They are closely related to Flynn's SIMD classification.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] Cray computers became famous for their vector-processing computers in the 1970s and 1980s.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] However, vector processors—both as CPUs and as full computer systems—have generally disappeared.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] Modern processor instruction sets do include some vector processing instructions, such as with Freescale Semiconductor's AltiVec and Intel's Streaming SIMD Extensions (SSE).
[src:dask/parallel-computing] Concurrent programming languages, libraries, APIs, and parallel programming models (such as algorithmic skeletons) have been created for programming parallel computers.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] These can generally be divided into classes based on the assumptions they make about the underlying memory architecture—shared memory, distributed memory, or shared distributed memory.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] Shared memory programming languages communicate by manipulating shared memory variables.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] Distributed memory uses message passing.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] POSIX Threads and OpenMP are two of the most widely used shared memory APIs, whereas Message Passing Interface (MPI) is the most widely used message-passing system API.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] One concept used in programming parallel programs is the future concept, where one part of a program promises to deliver a required datum to another part of a program at some future time.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] Efforts to standardize parallel programming include an open standard called OpenHMPP for hybrid multi-core parallel programming.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] The OpenHMPP directive-based programming model offers a syntax to efficiently offload computations on hardware accelerators and to optimize data movement to/from the hardware memory using remote procedure calls.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] The rise of consumer GPUs has led to support for compute kernels, either in graphics APIs (referred to as compute shaders), in dedicated APIs (such as OpenCL), or in other language extensions.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] Automatic parallelization of a sequential program by a compiler is the "holy grail" of parallel computing, especially with the aforementioned limit of processor frequency.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] Despite decades of work by compiler researchers, automatic parallelization has had only limited success.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] Mainstream parallel programming languages remain either explicitly parallel or (at best) partially implicit, in which a programmer gives the compiler directives for parallelization.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] A few fully implicit parallel programming languages exist—SISAL, Parallel Haskell, SequenceL, SystemC (for FPGAs), Mitrion-C, VHDL, and Verilog.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] As a computer system grows in complexity, the mean time between failures usually decreases.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] Application checkpointing is a technique whereby the computer system takes a "snapshot" of the application—a record of all current resource allocations and variable states, akin to a core dump—; this information can be used to restore the program if the computer should fail.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] Application checkpointing means that the program has to restart from only its last checkpoint rather than the beginning.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] While checkpointing provides benefits in a variety of situations, it is especially useful in highly parallel systems with a large number of processors used in high performance computing.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] As parallel computers become larger and faster, we are now able to solve problems that had previously taken too long to run.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] Fields as varied as bioinformatics (for protein folding and sequence analysis) and economics have taken advantage of parallel computing.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] Parallel computing can also be applied to the design of fault-tolerant computer systems, particularly via lockstep systems performing the same operation in parallel.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] This provides redundancy in case one component fails, and also allows automatic error detection and error correction if the results differ.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] These methods can be used to help prevent single-event upsets caused by transient errors.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] Although additional measures may be required in embedded or specialized systems, this method can provide a cost-effective approach to achieve n-modular redundancy in commercial off-the-shelf systems.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] The origins of true (MIMD) parallelism go back to Luigi Federico Menabrea and his *Sketch of the Analytic Engine Invented by Charles Babbage*.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] In 1957, Compagnie des Machines Bull announced the first computer architecture specifically designed for parallelism, the Gamma 60.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] It utilized a fork-join model and a "Program Distributor" to dispatch and collect data to and from independent processing units connected to a central memory.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] In April 1958, Stanley Gill (Ferranti) discussed parallel programming and the need for branching and waiting.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] Also in 1958, IBM researchers John Cocke and Daniel Slotnick discussed the use of parallelism in numerical calculations for the first time.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] Burroughs Corporation introduced the D825 in 1962, a four-processor computer that accessed up to 16 memory modules through a crossbar switch.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] In 1967, Amdahl and Slotnick published a debate about the feasibility of parallel processing at American Federation of Information Processing Societies Conference.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] It was during this debate that Amdahl's law was coined to define the limit of speed-up due to parallelism.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] In 1969, Honeywell introduced its first Multics system, a symmetric multiprocessor system capable of running up to eight processors in parallel.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] C.mmp, a multi-processor project at Carnegie Mellon University in the 1970s, was among the first multiprocessors with more than a few processors.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] The first bus-connected multiprocessor with snooping caches was the Synapse N+1 in 1984.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] SIMD parallel computers can be traced back to the 1970s.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] The motivation behind early SIMD computers was to amortize the gate delay of the processor's control unit over multiple instructions.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] In 1964, Slotnick had proposed building a massively parallel computer for the Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] His design was funded by the US Air Force, which was the earliest SIMD parallel-computing effort, ILLIAC IV.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] The key to its design was a fairly high parallelism, with up to 256 processors, which allowed the machine to work on large datasets in what would later be known as vector processing.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] However, ILLIAC IV was called "the most infamous of supercomputers", because the project was only one-fourth completed, but took 11 years and cost almost four times the original estimate.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] When it was finally ready to run its first real application in 1976, it was outperformed by existing commercial supercomputers such as the Cray-1.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] In the early 1970s, at the MIT Computer Science and Artificial Intelligence Laboratory, Marvin Minsky and Seymour Papert started developing the *Society of Mind* theory, which views the biological brain as massively parallel computer.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] In 1986, Minsky published *The Society of Mind*, which claims that "mind is formed from many little agents, each mindless by itself".
[src:dask/parallel-computing] The theory attempts to explain how what we call intelligence could be a product of the interaction of non-intelligent parts.
[src:dask/parallel-computing] Minsky says that the biggest source of ideas about the theory came from his work in trying to create a machine that uses a robotic arm, a video camera, and a computer to build with children's blocks.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] In computing, **scheduling** is the action of assigning resources to perform tasks.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] The resources may be processors, network links or expansion cards.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] The tasks may be threads, processes or data flows.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] The scheduling activity is carried out by a mechanism called a **scheduler**.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] Schedulers are often designed so as to keep all computer resources busy (as in load balancing), allow multiple users to share system resources effectively, or to achieve a target quality-of-service.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] Scheduling is fundamental to computation itself, and an intrinsic part of the execution model of a computer system; the concept of scheduling makes it possible to have computer multitasking with a single central processing unit (CPU).
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] In practice, these goals often conflict (e.g. throughput versus latency), thus a scheduler will implement a suitable compromise.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] Preference is measured by any one of the concerns mentioned above, depending upon the user's needs and objectives.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] In real-time environments, such as embedded systems for automatic control in industry (for example robotics), the scheduler also must ensure that processes can meet deadlines; this is crucial for keeping the system stable.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] Scheduled tasks can also be distributed to remote devices across a network and managed through an administrative back end.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] The scheduler is an operating system module that selects the next jobs to be admitted into the system and the next process to run.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] Operating systems may feature up to three distinct scheduler types: a *long-term scheduler* (also known as an admission scheduler or high-level scheduler), a *mid-term or medium-term scheduler*, and a *short-term scheduler*.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] The names suggest the relative frequency with which their functions are performed.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] The process scheduler is a part of the operating system that decides which process runs at a certain point in time.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] It usually has the ability to pause a running process, move it to the back of the running queue and start a new process; such a scheduler is known as a *preemptive scheduler*.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] If the scheduler cannot pause a running process and start a new process, the scheduler is a *cooperative scheduler*.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] We distinguish between *long-term scheduling*, *medium-term scheduling*, and *short-term scheduling* based on how often decisions must be made.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] Thus, this scheduler dictates what processes are to run on a system, the degree of concurrency to be supported at any one time – whether many or few processes are to be executed concurrently, and how the split between I/O-intensive and CPU-intensive processes is to be handled.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] The long-term scheduler is responsible for controlling the degree of multiprogramming.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] In general, most processes can be described as either I/O-bound or CPU-bound.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] An I/O-bound process is one that spends more of its time doing I/O than it spends doing computations.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] A CPU-bound process, in contrast, generates I/O requests infrequently, using more of its time doing computations.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] It is important that a long-term scheduler selects a good process mix of I/O-bound and CPU-bound processes.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] If all processes are I/O-bound, the ready queue will almost always be empty, and the short-term scheduler will have little to do.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] On the other hand, if all processes are CPU-bound, the I/O waiting queue will almost always be empty, devices will go unused, and again the system will be unbalanced.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] The system with the best performance will thus have a combination of CPU-bound and I/O-bound processes.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] In modern operating systems, this is used to make sure that real-time processes get enough CPU time to finish their tasks.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] Long-term scheduling is also important in large-scale systems such as batch processing systems, computer clusters, supercomputers, and render farms.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] For example, in concurrent systems, coscheduling of interacting processes is often required to prevent them from blocking due to waiting on each other.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] In these cases, special-purpose job scheduler software is typically used to assist these functions, in addition to any underlying admission scheduling support in the operating system.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] Some operating systems only allow new tasks to be added if it is sure all real-time deadlines can still be met.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] The specific heuristic algorithm used by an operating system to accept or reject new tasks is the *admission control mechanism*.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] The *medium-term scheduler* temporarily removes processes from main memory and places them in secondary memory (such as a hard disk drive) or vice versa, which is commonly referred to as *swapping out* or *swapping in* (also incorrectly as *paging out* or *paging in*).
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] In many systems today (those that support mapping virtual address space to secondary storage other than the swap file), the medium-term scheduler may actually perform the role of the long-term scheduler, by treating binaries as *swapped-out processes* upon their execution.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] In this way, when a segment of the binary is required, it can be swapped in on demand, or *lazy loaded*, also called demand paging.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] The *short-term scheduler* (also known as the *CPU scheduler*) decides which of the ready, in-memory processes is to be executed (allocated a CPU) after a clock interrupt, an I/O interrupt, an operating system call or another form of signal.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] Thus, the short-term scheduler makes scheduling decisions much more frequently than the long-term or mid-term schedulers – A scheduling decision will, at a minimum, have to be made after every time slice, and these are very short.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] This scheduler can be preemptive, implying that it is capable of forcibly removing processes from a CPU when it decides to allocate that CPU to another process, or non-preemptive (also known as *voluntary* or *co-operative*), in which case the scheduler is unable to *force* processes off the CPU.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] Another component that is involved in the CPU-scheduling function is the dispatcher, which is the module that gives control of the CPU to the process selected by the short-term scheduler.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] It receives control in kernel mode as the result of an interrupt or system call.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] The dispatcher should be as fast as possible since it is invoked during every process switch.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] During the context switches, the processor is virtually idle for a fraction of time, thus unnecessary context switches should be avoided.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] The time it takes for the dispatcher to stop one process and start another is known as the *dispatch latency*.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] A **scheduling discipline** (also called **scheduling policy** or **scheduling algorithm**) is an algorithm used for distributing resources among parties that simultaneously and asynchronously request them.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] Scheduling disciplines are used in routers (to handle packet traffic) as well as in operating systems (to share CPU time among both threads and processes), disk drives (I/O scheduling), printers (print spooler), most embedded systems, etc.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] The main purposes of scheduling algorithms are to minimize resource starvation and to ensure fairness amongst the parties utilizing the resources.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] Scheduling deals with the problem of deciding which of the outstanding requests is to be allocated resources.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] There are many different scheduling algorithms.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] In this section, we introduce several of them.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] In packet-switched computer networks and other statistical multiplexing, the notion of a **scheduling algorithm** is used as an alternative to first-come first-served queuing of data packets.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] The simplest best-effort scheduling algorithms are round-robin, fair queuing (a max-min fair scheduling algorithm), proportional-fair scheduling and maximum throughput.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] If differentiated or guaranteed quality of service is offered, as opposed to best-effort communication, weighted fair queuing may be utilized.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] In advanced packet radio wireless networks such as HSDPA (High-Speed Downlink Packet Access) 3.5G cellular system, **channel-dependent scheduling** may be used to take advantage of channel state information.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] If the channel conditions are favourable, the throughput and system spectral efficiency may be increased.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] In even more advanced systems such as LTE, the scheduling is combined by channel-dependent packet-by-packet dynamic channel allocation, or by assigning OFDMA multi-carriers or other frequency-domain equalization components to the users that best can utilize them.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] Earliest deadline first (EDF) or *least time to go* is a dynamic scheduling algorithm used in real-time operating systems to place processes in a priority queue.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] Whenever a scheduling event occurs (a task finishes, a new task is released, etc.), the queue will be searched for the process closest to its deadline, which will be the next to be scheduled for execution.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] With this strategy the scheduler arranges processes with the least estimated processing time remaining to be next in the queue.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] This requires advanced knowledge or estimations about the time required for a process to complete.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] The operating system assigns a fixed-priority rank to every process, and the scheduler arranges the processes in the ready queue in order of their priority.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] Lower-priority processes get interrupted by incoming higher-priority processes.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] The scheduler assigns a fixed time unit per process, and cycles through them.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] If the process completes within that time slice, it gets terminated otherwise, it is rescheduled after giving a chance to all other processes.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] This is used for situations in which processes are easily divided into different groups.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] For example, a common division is made between foreground (interactive) processes and background (batch) processes.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] These two types of processes have different response-time requirements and so may have different scheduling needs.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] It is very useful for shared memory problems.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] A work-conserving scheduler is a scheduler that always tries to keep the scheduled resources busy if there are submitted jobs ready to be scheduled.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] In contrast, a non-work-conserving scheduler is a scheduler that, in some cases, may leave the scheduled resources idle despite the presence of jobs ready to be scheduled.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] A very common method in embedded systems is to schedule jobs manually.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] This can, for example, be done in a time-multiplexed fashion.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] Sometimes the kernel is divided in three or more parts: Manual scheduling, preemptive and interrupt level.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] Exact methods for scheduling jobs are often proprietary.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] When designing an operating system, a programmer must consider which scheduling algorithm will perform best for the use the system is going to see.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] There is no universal *best* scheduling algorithm, and many operating systems use extended or combinations of the scheduling algorithms above.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] For example, Windows NT/XP/Vista uses a multilevel feedback queue, a combination of fixed-priority preemptive scheduling, round-robin, and first-in, first-out algorithms.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] In this system, threads can dynamically increase or decrease in priority depending on if it has been serviced already or if it has been waiting extensively.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] Every priority level is represented by its own queue, with round-robin scheduling among the high-priority threads and FIFO among the lower-priority ones.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] In this sense, response time is short for most threads, and short but critical system threads get completed very quickly.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] Since threads can only use one time unit of the round-robin in the highest-priority queue, starvation can be a problem for longer high-priority threads.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] The algorithm used may be as simple as round-robin in which each process is given equal time (for instance, 1 ms, usually between 1 ms and 100 ms) in a cycling list.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] So, process A executes for 1 ms, then process B, then process C, then back to process A.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] More advanced algorithms take into account process priority, or the importance of the process.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] This allows some processes to use more time than others.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] The kernel always uses whatever resources it needs to ensure proper functioning of the system, and so can be said to have infinite priority.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] In SMP systems, processor affinity is considered to increase overall system performance, even if it may cause a process itself to run more slowly.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] This generally improves performance by reducing cache thrashing.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] IBM OS/360 was available with three different schedulers.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] Later virtual storage versions of MVS added a *Workload Manager* feature to the scheduler, which schedules processor resources according to an elaborate scheme defined by the installation.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] Very early MS-DOS and Microsoft Windows systems were non-multitasking, and as such did not feature a scheduler.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] Windows 3.1x used a non-preemptive scheduler, meaning that it did not interrupt programs.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] It relied on the program to end or tell the OS that it didn't need the processor so that it could move on to another process.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] This is usually called cooperative multitasking.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] Windows 95 introduced a rudimentary preemptive scheduler; however, for legacy support opted to let 16-bit applications run without preemption.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] Windows NT-based operating systems use a multilevel feedback queue.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] 32 priority levels are defined, 0 through 31, with priorities 0 through 15 being *normal* priorities and priorities 16 through 31 being soft real-time priorities, requiring privileges to assign.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] User interfaces and APIs work with priority classes for the process and the threads in the process, which are then combined by the system into the absolute priority level.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] The scheduler was modified in Windows Vista to use the cycle counter register of modern processors to keep track of exactly how many CPU cycles a thread has executed, rather than just using an interval-timer interrupt routine.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] Vista also uses a priority scheduler for the I/O queue so that disk defragmenters and other such programs do not interfere with foreground operations.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] Mac OS 9 uses cooperative scheduling for threads, where one process controls multiple cooperative threads, and also provides preemptive scheduling for multiprocessing tasks.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] The kernel schedules multiprocessing tasks using a preemptive scheduling algorithm.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] All Process Manager processes run within a special multiprocessing task, called the *blue task*.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] Those processes are scheduled cooperatively, using a round-robin scheduling algorithm; a process yields control of the processor to another process by explicitly calling a blocking function such as `WaitNextEvent`.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] Each process has its own copy of the Thread Manager that schedules that process's threads cooperatively; a thread yields control of the processor to another thread by calling `YieldToAnyThread` or `YieldToThread`.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] macOS uses a multilevel feedback queue, with four priority bands for threads – normal, system high priority, kernel mode only, and real-time.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] Threads are scheduled preemptively; macOS also supports cooperatively scheduled threads in its implementation of the Thread Manager in Carbon.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] Threads are primarily of interest for applications that currently consist of several asynchronous processes.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] These applications might impose a lighter load on the system if converted to a multithreaded structure.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] AIX 5 implements the following scheduling policies: FIFO, round robin, and fair round robin.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] The FIFO policy has three different implementations: FIFO, FIFO2, and FIFO3.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] The round robin policy is named SCHED_RR in AIX, and the fair round robin is called SCHED_OTHER.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] Linux 1.2 used a round-robin scheduling policy.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] Linux 2.2 added scheduling classes and support for symmetric multiprocessing (SMP).
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] In Linux 2.4, an O(n) scheduler with a multilevel feedback queue with priority levels ranging from 0 to 140 was used; 0–99 are reserved for real-time tasks and 100–140 are considered nice task levels.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] For real-time tasks, the time quantum for switching processes was approximately 200 ms, and for nice tasks approximately 10 ms.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] The scheduler ran through the run queue of all ready processes, letting the highest priority processes go first and run through their time slices, after which they will be placed in an expired queue.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] When the active queue is empty, the expired queue will become the active queue and vice versa.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] However, some enterprise Linux distributions such as SUSE Linux Enterprise Server replaced this scheduler with a backport of the O(1) scheduler (which was maintained by Alan Cox in his Linux 2.4-ac Kernel series) to the Linux 2.4 kernel used by the distribution.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] In versions 2.6.0 to 2.6.22, the kernel used an O(1) scheduler developed by Ingo Molnar and many other kernel developers during the Linux 2.5 development.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] For many kernels in this time frame, Con Kolivas developed patch sets which improved interactivity with this scheduler or even replaced it with his own schedulers.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] Con Kolivas' work, most significantly his implementation of fair scheduling named Rotating Staircase Deadline (RSDL), inspired Ingo Molnár to develop the Completely Fair Scheduler (CFS) as a replacement for the earlier O(1) scheduler, crediting Kolivas in his announcement.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] CFS is the first implementation of a fair queuing process scheduler widely used in a general-purpose operating system.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] The CFS uses a well-studied, classic scheduling algorithm called fair queuing originally invented for packet networks.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] Fair queuing had been previously applied to CPU scheduling under the name stride scheduling.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] The fair queuing CFS scheduler has a scheduling complexity of $O(\log N)$ , where N is the number of tasks in the runqueue.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] Choosing a task can be done in constant time, but reinserting a task after it has run requires $O(\log N)$ operations, because the run queue is implemented as a red–black tree.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] The Brain Fuck Scheduler, also created by Con Kolivas, is an alternative to the CFS.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] In 2023, Peter Zijlstra proposed replacing CFS with an earliest eligible virtual deadline first scheduling (EEVDF) process scheduler.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] The aim was to remove the need for CFS *latency nice* patches.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] Linux 6.12 added support for scheduler extensions that can be added from userspace; this mechanism is known as sched_ext.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] An eBPF program can be loaded into the kernel to implement a scheduling policy.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] These schedulers can replace the default scheduler.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] FreeBSD uses a multilevel feedback queue with priorities ranging from 0–255.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] 0–63 are reserved for interrupts, 64–127 for the top half of the kernel, 128–159 for real-time user threads, 160–223 for time-shared user threads, and 224–255 for idle user threads.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] Also, like Linux, it uses the active queue setup, but it also has an idle queue.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] NetBSD uses a multilevel feedback queue with priorities ranging from 0–223.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] 0–63 are reserved for time-shared threads (default, SCHED_OTHER policy), 64–95 for user threads that entered kernel space, 96–128 for kernel threads, 128–191 for user real-time threads (SCHED_FIFO and SCHED_RR policies), and 192–223 for software interrupts.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] Solaris uses a multilevel feedback queue with priorities ranging between 0 and 169.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] Priorities 0–59 are reserved for time-shared threads, 60–99 for system threads, 100–159 for real-time threads, and 160–169 for low priority interrupts.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] Unlike Linux, when a process is done using its time quantum, it is given a new priority and put back in the queue.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] Solaris 9 introduced two new scheduling classes, namely fixed-priority class and fair share class.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] The threads with fixed priority have the same priority range as that of the time-sharing class, but their priorities are not dynamically adjusted.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] The fair scheduling class uses CPU *shares* to prioritize threads for scheduling decisions.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] CPU shares indicate the entitlement to CPU resources.
[src:dask/scheduling-computing] They are allocated to a set of processes, which are collectively known as a project.
